              "よかったら",
              "明日",
              "また",
              "行きましょう"
            ]
          ],
          "explanation": "〜たら is a conditional ('if'). いい → よかったら (irregular: よい stem + かったら). 〜ましょう is a volitional invitation ('let's'). 明日 can appear before or after the conditional. Distractor よければ is the 〜ば conditional — also valid Japanese, but doesn't match the target."
        },
        {
          "q": "Leg 6: I walked home while listening to music.",
          "segments": [
            "音楽",
            "を",
            "聞きながら",
            "歩いて",
            "帰りました"
          ],
          "distractors": [
            "聞いて",
            "に",
            "帰って"
          ],
          "explanation": "〜ながら means 'while doing'. 聞く → 聞きながら (ます-stem + ながら). 歩いて帰りました uses て-form to connect 'walked' and 'went home'. Distractor 聞いて would make it sequential ('listened, then walked') instead of simultaneous."
        },
        {
          "q": "Leg 7: Even though I was tired, I had too much fun and couldn't go home.",
          "segments": [
            "つかれた",
            "のに",
            "楽しすぎて",
            "帰れませんでした"
          ],
          "distractors": [
            "ので",
            "楽しくて",
            "帰りませんでした"
          ],
          "explanation": "のに means 'even though' (concessive). 楽しい → 楽し + すぎる (too much) → 楽しすぎて (te-form giving reason = 'it was too fun so...'). 帰る → 帰れる (potential) → 帰れませんでした (past negative potential = 'couldn't go home'). Distractor ので ('because') reverses the logic. Distractor 帰りませんでした ('didn't go home') loses the nuance of inability."
        },
        {
          "q": "Leg 8: My mother made me write a letter to my friend.",
          "segments": [
            "母",
            "に",
            "友だち",
            "へ",
            "手紙",
            "を",
            "書かせられました"
          ],
          "distractors": [
            "が",
            "書きました",
            "書かれました"
          ],
          "explanation": "書かせられました is the causative-passive of 書く: 書か (あ-stem) + せ (causative) + られ (passive) + ました. 母に marks who caused the action. へ marks the recipient direction. Distractor 書かれました is plain passive ('was written by'); distractor 書きました is just polite past ('wrote'). This is the hardest pattern in N4 — you made it to the finish line! 🎉"
        }
      ]
